    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Sunday Evening</date>
                    <salute>My dear George</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>If you are not pledged to M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Salts agents,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> as your solicitors, I think it is a very great pity that you do not employ M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Hacon, whom both William &amp; I know is trustworthy.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/> M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Salt’s agents will be complete strangers, &amp; we have no claim or tie on them.</p>
                    <p>About 40 years ago I went to their agents, &amp; a more odious set of men I never saw, so that I w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. have nothing more to do with them.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/> About a year ago I saw the death of M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Salt of Shrewsbury in the newspapers, &amp; I do not know whether there is now any Salt in the firm.—<ref target="#foot.f5"/> Of course the agents may now prove to be the most respectable people; but I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> employ M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Hacon for selling the house.—<ref target="#foot.f6"/></p>
                    <p>I fear that this business will give you a great deal of trouble, &amp; it is very unfortunate William being tied by the leg—<ref target="#foot.f7"/></p>
<p>Your affectionate Father | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">2.1 of men] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>
            
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13303.xml">letter from G. H. Darwin, [29 August 1881]</ref>. In 1881, the Sunday before 29 August was 28 August.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4154.xml">George Moultrie Salt</ref> was partner in the firm <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4153.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Salt &amp; Sons</ref>, Shrewsbury; the London agents were Paterson, Snow, &amp; Bloxam of 25 Lincoln’s Inn Fields. George was an executor of the will of <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1211.xml">Erasmus Alvey Darwin</ref>, who died on 26 August 1881 (CD’s ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2042.xml">William Mackmurdo Hacon</ref> and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1245.xml">William Erasmus Darwin</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">In the 1840s, Salt’s London agents were Hawkins, Bloxam, &amp; Stoker of 3 New Boswell Court, Lincoln’s Inn (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4613.xml"><hi rend="italic">Law list</hi></ref> 1841). </note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4157.xml">William Salt</ref>, a partner in the firm <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4153.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Salt &amp; Sons</ref>, died on 22 May 1881 at Shrewsbury (<hi rend="italic">England &amp; Wales, national probate calendar (index of wills and administrations), 1858–1966</hi> (Ancestry.com, accessed 9 October 2019)).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1211.xml">Erasmus Alvey Darwin</ref> had lived at 6 Queen Anne Street, London.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7">William and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1240.xml">Sara Darwin</ref> were about to depart for France.</note>
            
        </div>
    
